Lesson 1: Comparing and Contrasting Different Types of Social Engineering Techniques

*Social Engineering attacks leverage the weakest link, which is typically the human user. If an attacker can get a user to reveal information it is much easier for the attacker to cause harm than it is by using some other method of reconnaissance. Social engineering can be accomplished through email or misdirection of web pages, prompting a user to click something that leads to the attacker gaining information.


1.1: Social Engineering Fundamentals

*Social engineering is the act of manipulating users into revealing confidential information or performing other actions detrimental to the user. Common social engineering techniques include phishing and smear phishing, smishing, vishing, spam, spam over internet messaging (SPIM), dumpster diving, should surfing, pharming, tailgating, eliciting information, whaling, prepending, identity fraud, invoice scams, credential harvesting, reconnaissance, hoax, impersonation or pretexting, eavesdropping, baiting, watering hole attack, and typo squatting.


Phishing and Spear Phishing
---------------------------
Phishing, is the attempt at fraudulently obtaining private information. A phisher usually masquerades as someone else. There are two main differences between phishing and pretexting. Pretexting, is the act of impersonating or spoofing someone else's identity. An attacker could impersonate and employee of a company or business partner to attempt to steal sensitive data from the victim. Phishing is usually done by electronic communication, not in person. Second, little information about the target is necessary. A phisher might target thousands of individuals without much concern as to their background.


Smishing
--------
Because phishing has been an effective tactic for threat actors they have found ways other than using email to fool their victims into following malicious links or activating malware from emails. A number of phishing campaigns have used short message service (SMS) to send malware or malicious links to mobile devices. This social engineering technique is also known as smishing.


Vishing
-------
Phishing attacks can also be accomplished by telephone conversations. Phone or voice phishing known as vishing works in the same manner as phishing but is initiated by a phone call often using VoIP systems.


Spam and Spam over Internet Messaging (SPIM)
--------------------------------------------
Spam has traditionally been the term used to describe unwanted and unsolicited email messages. However emails messages are not the only way that attackers or malicious users send spam. Users may also receive spam via social media sites and instant/internet messaging applications. 


Dumpster Diving
---------------
When a person literally scavenges for private information in garbage and recycling containers, that is known as dumpster diving.


Shoulder Surfing
----------------
Occurs when a person uses direct observation to find out a targets password, pin, or other such authentication methods.


Pharming
--------
Used to describe a threat actor redirecting a victim from a valid website or resource to a malicious one that could be made to appear as the valid site to the user. From there and attempt is made to extract confidential information from the user or to install malware in the victims system. Pharming can be done by altering the hosts file on a victims system, through DNS poisoning, or by exploiting a vulnerability in a DNS server.


Piggybacking or Tailgating
--------------------------
When an unauthorized person tags along with an authorized person to gain entry to a restricted area, usually with that persons consent, that person is piggybacking. Tailgating is essentially the same with one difference, it is usually without the authorized persons consent.


Eliciting Information
---------------------
Key components of social engineering are how someone influences, interrogates, and impersonates others. Eliciting information is the act of gaining knowledge or information from people. In most cases an attacker gets information from the victim without directly asking for that particular information. Interrogators pay close attention to the victims body language, the coloring in the victims skin, the direction of the victims head and eyes, movement of the victims hands and feet, and the victims mouth and lip expressions.


Whaling
-------
Whaling is similar to phishing and spear phishing however with whaling the attack is targeted at high=profile business executives and key individuals in a corporation.


Prepending
----------
You can often configure your email servers or email cloud services to prepend a message in the email subject line to identify emails that are coming from outside of the organization. This technique is also known as prepending.


Impersonation or Pretexting
--------------------------
Pretexting is a type of social engineering attack in which a person incents a scenario or pretext in the hope of persuading a victim to divulge information. By impersonating the appropriate personnel or third party entities a person performing a pretext hopes to obtain records about an organization, its data, and its personnel.


Baiting
-------
Is a strategy in which a malicious individual leaves malware-infected removable media such as a USB drive or optical disc lying around in plain view. It might have an interesting logo or distinctive look about it. When a person takes it and connects it to his or her computer the malware infects the computer and attempts to take control of it and/or the network the computer is a member of.


Watering Hole Attack
--------------------
Is a strategy that targets users based on the common websites that they frequent. The attacker loads malware beforehand on one or more websites in the hopes that the user will access those sites and activate the malware, ultimately infecting the users system and possibly spreading through the network.


Typo Squatting
--------------
Is a technique used by adversaries that leverages human error when typing a URL in their web browser. For instance, users often enter typos or a wrong URL for a given website.


1.2: User Security Awareness Education

*The user could be the single most exploitable resource of a company. People aren't computes, some might be compared to robots but no matter how logical and discipled a person might be there is always the potential for human error. There are several roadblocks when it comes to user training. The first is organizational acceptance, are the executives of a company on board with the idea? Then there are the employees to be trained themselves. Some will put up a fight when it comes to education, the secret ingredient here is to pique the interest of the users. Some basic rules you can convey when training employees are never under any circumstances give out any authentication details such as passwords, pins, company ID, tokens, and smart cards. 

